design_1.name: Lynx
design_1.description: Czech Republic proposal; a fictional substance in the novel Továrna na absolutno by Karel Čapek.

design_2.name: Eridanus
design_2.description: The name was originally Arabic: آخر النهر āẖir an-nahr ('river's end').

design_3.name: Cassiopeia
design_3.description: Apparently first applied to η Cassiopeiae in the Skalnate Pleso Atlas of the Heavens published in 1950, but is not known prior to that.

design_15.name: Scorpius
design_15.description: The traditional name of the β Scorpii system has been rendered Akrab and Elakrab, derived (like Acrab) from Arabic: العقرب al-ʿaqrab ('the scorpion').

design_25.name: Crux
design_25.description: Acrux is a modern contraction of the Bayer designation, coined in the 19th century, but which entered into common use only by the mid-20th century.

design_6.name: Cancer
design_6.description: The name was originally Arabic: الزبانى az-zubāná ('the claws').

design_7.name: Canis Major
design_7.description: The name is originally from Arabic: عذارى ʿaḏārá ('virgins'). In the Calendarium of Al Achsasi Al Mouakket, it is designated أول العذاري awwil al-ʿaḏāriyy, translated into Latin as Prima Virginum ('first virgin').

design_37.name: Andromeda
design_37.description: The name was originally Arabic: الذيل aḏ-ḏayl (the train, lit. 'the tail').

design_9.name: Taurus
design_9.description: The name is originally from Arabic: عين ʿayn ('eye') and was reviewed and adopted by the Working Group on Star Names.

design_34.name: Sagittarius
design_34.description: From Arabic: عين الرامي ʿayn ar-rāmī ('eye of the archer').

design_38.name: Antlia
design_38.description: Colombian proposal; named after a mythical village from the novel Cien anos de soledad (One Hundred Years of Solitude) by Gabriel García Márquez.

design_51.name: Camelopardalis
design_51.description: German proposal; named after Mago National Park, a national park in Ethiopia noted for its giraffes (Camelopardalis is Latin for 'giraffe').
